\if0\anon
{
 \title{\bf Domain Adaptation Optimized for Robustness in Mixture Populations}
 \maketitle
} \fi

\bigskip
\begin{abstract}
Multi-source domain adaptation is essential for the leveraging of diverse institutional data sources to advance accurate prediction on some target. In many such applications, the target population can be approximated by a mixture of the sources, but the domain adaptation in this scenario is hindered by distributional heterogeneity, the absence of gold-standard outcomes in target data, and the lack of methods exploiting such source-mixing structures. To address this, we introduce a novel \emph{$(X,Y)$-coupled regime} for multi-source domain adaptation, which formalizes how strongly the individualized, source-mixture weights inferred from the distribution of target covariates $X$ should also govern the conditional model of $Y\mid X$ on target. Based on this, we propose a new framework called \textbf{D}omain adaptation \textbf{O}ptimized for \textbf{R}obustness in \textbf{M}ixture populations (DORM). Leveraging partially labeled source data, DORM first constructs an initial target outcome model under the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime assuming that the joint distribution of $(X,Y)$ on target can be well-approximated by the mixture of the sources. It then introduces a partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime allowing for deviations from this assumption and constructs an uncertainty set for the target distributions partially identified in this regime. Finally, DORM incorporates adversarial learning to obtain an estimator that optimizes the worst-case predictive performance among the uncertainty set. The procedure can be assisted by surrogates to enhance transferability, and is further extended to accommodate latent intrinsic sources underlying observed source data and adjustment for pre-mixing covariates, improving flexibility and feasibility in practice. We establish asymptotic convergence and characterize predictive accuracy of our method through theoretical studies. Extensive simulations and a real-world study with Biobank datasets demonstrate the superior performance of DORM relative to existing approaches. 

\end{abstract}

%Multi-source domain adaptation is essential for leveraging diverse institutional data. In many applications, the target population approximates a mixture of sources, yet adaptation is hindered by heterogeneity, absence of target outcomes, and lack of methods exploiting source-mixing structures. To address this, we introduce a novel (X,Y)-coupled regime, formalizing how strongly individualized source-mixture weights inferred from target covariates X govern the conditional model of Y given X. Based on this, we propose Domain adaptation Optimized for Robustness in Mixture populations (DORM). Leveraging partially labeled source data, DORM first constructs an initial target model under the fully coupled regime. It then introduces a partially coupled regime allowing deviations from this assumption, constructing an uncertainty set for partially identified target distributions. DORM incorporates adversarial learning to optimize worst-case predictive performance within this set. The procedure accommodates surrogates, latent intrinsic sources, and pre-mixing covariates. We establish asymptotic convergence and predictive accuracy theoretically. Extensive simulations and a real-world Biobank study demonstrate DORM's superior performance relative to existing approaches.

%\noindent%
{\it Keywords:} Domain adaptation, Multi-source data, Mixture population, Distributional robustness.
%\vfill

