\section{Introduction}\label{sec:background}

% {\color{red} Last things to check: updating the references; notations like $|$ versus $\mid$. Still multiple equation label issue.}

Integrative analysis of multi-institutional biobank-linked electronic health record (EHR) data holds immense potential to advance precision medicine. By leveraging large and diverse datasets, such analyses can uncover novel insights and improve risk prediction. However, ensuring the generalizability of these models to future target populations remains a significant challenge. The difficulty stems from the heterogeneity among the population, the presence of bias in training sources, and the potential underrepresentation of future target populations within existing datasets. %For instance, the UK Biobank (UKB) comprises over 90\% participants of European descent, with less than 4\% of African or South Asian ancestry. 
This poses substantial challenges for genetic risk modeling in underrepresented populations, particularly for admixed individuals whose genomes are mosaics of multiple ancestries and who constitute a growing share of the U.S. population. Since the allele-frequencies, linkage disequilibrium (LD) structures and genetic effect sizes can vary across ancestries \citep{west2017genomics,martin2019clinical}, developing ancestry-specific genetic risk scores (GRS) is a natural strategy. However, admixed ancestries typically have much smaller sample sizes than those of parental populations, making it challenging to optimize risk prediction on them. Consequently, most existing studies have historically excluded admixed individuals due to limited methods for addressing this issue \citep{atkinson2021tractor,sirugo2019missing,martin2018properties}. This invokes the need to systematically leverage larger parental data sources to assist risk modeling on the admixed target viewed as a mixture of sources. Moreover, populations vary inherently across biobanks, each enrolling a distinct demographic composition; addressing such mixture-induced heterogeneity is crucial for powerful and generalizable prediction on diverse populations \citep{de2021developing}. 

Optimizing prediction performance for target domains using multiple heterogeneous source domains has become a focal point of research in recent years. In domain adaptation, knowledge transfer methods leverage multiple labeled sources to improve performance on a target population. For example, \cite{li2022transfer} and \cite{tian2023transfer} leveraged information through sparse shrinkage and introduced algorithm-free procedures to detect transferable sources. \cite{cai2022semi} and \cite{he2024transfusion} improved this so-called Trans-Lasso framework by addressing covariate shift and semi-supervised problems. \cite{gu2025robust} and \cite{lin2024profiled} further developed angle-based and profile transfer learning. \cite{li2025multi} studied multi-source domain generalization using tensor completion. Although these approaches demonstrate solid utility, they %assume the outcome model coefficients of the target population are close to those of the sources and 
require observations of labels in the target data. Importantly, these existing approaches do not directly exploit \emph{source-mixing} structure of the target to enable transfer under severe label scarcity.

When no accurate outcomes (gold-standard labels) are available in the target data, unsupervised domain adaptation (UDA) addresses distributional shift between labeled sources and an unlabeled target. Typical UDA strategies include moment matching via maximum mean discrepancy \citep{long2018conditional}, feature-level adversarial learning \citep{ganin2016domain}, and so on. \cite{liu2023augmented}, \cite{wang2023pseudo} and others focused on addressing covariate shift between the source and target, without simultaneously accommodating outcome model heterogeneity. \cite{jeong2024out} and \cite{jin2025beyond} proposed and utilized a random distribution shift model to achieve generalizable domain adaptation. However, these methods are not designed to exploit the multi-source joint  mixture structure of the target distribution for model identification and knowledge transfer.

To improve generalizability of existing domain adaptation approaches across a range of unknown future populations, group distributionally robust optimization (DRO) and maximin frameworks have been developed. These methods define uncertainty sets as mixtures over observed sources and minimize worst-case performance \citep{sagawa2019distributionally,ijcai2023p162}. \cite{meinshausen2015maximin} introduced a maximin framework to maximize the minimum reduced variance of a linear model across multiple data sources; \cite{guo2022statistical} and \cite{wang2025distributionally} further developed high-dimensional regression and general machine learning methods for distributionally robust domain adaptation to some unlabeled target data. These methods often achieve robustness at the cost of being overly conservative due to relatively large uncertainty sets. Several recent works incorporate side information to shrink uncertainty sets, e.g. using a small labeled target subset to guide group DRO \citep{xiong2023distributionally}. Still, these strategies require a non-negligible number of labeled target samples, which is often unavailable for small, admixed, or otherwise underrepresented targets.

% When prior knowledge about future target populations is available, it is beneficial to incorporate this knowledge to reduce the conservativeness of DRO methods. For instance, \cite{xiong2023distributionally} utilized a small subset of labeled observations in the target data to guide the uncertainty set in group DRO. \cite{mo2024minimax} introduced a group minimax regret framework and replaced the baseline null model in maximin regression with the empirical risk minimizer. However, these existing methods still require a sufficiently large number of observed labeled samples from the target to effectively train some target-only model, raising a challenge of the typical absence or scarcity of labels of admixed ancestries.

%Motivated by the derivation of generalizable GRS for admixture populations, 


% {\color{red} Comment: I feel the key points are overwhelmed in the following paragraphs. These following part could be more concise. To me, the first key point is to introduce the joint-mixing regime which facilitates identification of a target model even without labels. Such mixture regime has not been considered in the context of transfer learning before. Based on this, we propose a partially coupling framework (or regime) accommodating both the joint-mixing and conditional-mixing regimes. In this regime, the target model is ...

% }

In this paper, we propose a novel \emph{$(X,Y)$-coupled regime} for multi-source domain adaptation that quantifies how strongly the source-mixture weights learned from the distributions of {target covariates} $\PP_X^{(0)}$ and source covariates $\PP_X^{(l)}$'s can govern the {conditional model} $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$ on target. As an ideal endpoint, the \emph{fully $(X,Y)$-coupled} (joint-mixing) regime assumes target joint distribution $\PP_{X,Y}^{(0)}$ is a mixture of source joint distributions, under which $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$ is fully identifiable even without observation of $Y$ in target data. At the other endpoint, the \emph{fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled} regime treats $\PP_X^{(0)}$ as fully uninformative for $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$; most existing multi-source domain adaptation methods are developed for this fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled endpoint \citep[etc.]{xiong2023distributionally,li2025multi,wang2025distributionally}. Our main setup is a \emph{partially $(X,Y)$-coupled} regime that interpolates between these two endpoints through a decoupling budget, yielding an estimable, data-adaptive link between covariate shift and conditional model drift. To our best knowledge, such a regime has not been considered in the domain adaptation literature.

Based on this new regime, we develop a novel framework called \textbf{D}omain adaptation \textbf{O}ptimized for \textbf{R}obustness in \textbf{M}ixture populations (DORM). Guided by the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime, DORM first leverages generic machine learning (ML) methods to approximate target $\PP\uz_X$ as a mixture of the source $\PP\ul_X$. Then DORM constructs the partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime by allowing deviation from the joint-mixing endpoint with a decoupling budget, and incorporates adversarial learning to optimize the worst-case performance under this partially identified regime. The approach is assisted by auxiliary covariates to stabilize transfer and incorporates double machine learning (DML) to reduce errors in ML estimation, allowing for flexible model specification. We further develop two methodological extensions: intrinsic sources and pre-mixing covariates, which improve the flexibility and feasibility of DORM in practice. Through theoretical analysis, DORM is shown to achieve desirable convergence to its population value, as well as good predictive performance on the target close to the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled endpoint. In terms of out-of-distribution generalization, DORM outperforms existing methods in simulation and real-world studies. 

DORM fills the gap of existing multi-source domain adaptation tools in addressing the source-mixture type of target. Several recent multi-source transfer procedures rely on sufficiently many labeled target outcomes for knowledge transfer \citep{li2022transfer,xiong2023distributionally}, limiting their usability when $Y$ is scarce or unavailable in the target data.  Meanwhile, existing domain generalization and DRO methods effectively operate near the fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled viewpoint: they construct uncertainty sets for $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$ that span nearly the full simplex of the source conditional models, largely independently of $\PP_X^{(0)}$ \citep{guo2022statistical,wang2025distributionally}. This could lead to over-conservative models when the target truly arises as a mixture of sources.
%These existing methods are not effectively utilizing mixture structure in the target data. 
In contrast to them, DORM leverages the joint-source-mixing structure encoded in $X$ to tighten the uncertainty set of target distributions, while retaining adversarial conditional mixtures to guard against unidentifiable deviations from the joint mixing regime. This partial $(X,Y)$-coupling yields a principled trade-off between predictive accuracy for structured mixture targets and out-of-distribution robustness. Importantly, DORM achieves knowledge transfer leveraging information of $X$ from the target rather than directly assembling the conditional models or regression coefficients from the sources as in \cite{gu2025robust,xiong2023distributionally} and others, mitigating the gap in the literature of multi-source domain adaptation for mixture populations.


% DORM fills the gap of existing multi-source domain adaptation tools in addressing the source-mixture type of target. Compared to DRO type of work,   Compared to existing approaches like \cite{li2022transfer} and \cite{xiong2023distributionally}, which rely on sufficient labeled target samples for high-dimensional regression, a main advantage of leveraging the source-mixing structure in DORM is the realization of knowledge transfer in a more challenging setup with scarcity or even absence of labeled target samples, while still accounting for the outcome model shift between the sources and the target. 
%Although such challenges are frequently encountered in various application scenarios such as EHR and biobank studies, effective and robust knowledge transfer has not been easily achieved in this scenario {\darkred due to the lack of methods leveraging the coupling between covariate distribution and conditional distribution to infer the outcome model on the target population. }
% Our proposed scheme mitigates the current gap in literature by mixing the joint distribution of $(X,Y)$ from the sources but not directly assembling the regression coefficients like \cite{xiong2023distributionally} or \cite{lin2024profiled}.

In addition, although surrogate-assisted learning has already raised great research interest \citep[e.g.]{hou2023surrogate,xia2024prediction}, there is still a lack of work utilizing surrogates to assist multi-source domain adaptation. Our work fills this gap by effectively leveraging the surrogate (auxiliary) features to identify source-mixing approximation for the target domain. Since distributional shift of the high-dimensional features across the source and target domains could cause excessive bias, we address this technical challenge through a double machine learning (DML) framework shown to be insensitive to the errors of nuisance ML models used for covariate shift correction. 


\section{DORM: definition and identification}\label{sec:def}

Suppose that we have access to $L$ source datasets $\{X^{(l)}, Y^{(l)}\}_{1 \leqslant l \leqslant L}$ collected from different sub-populations. For $1 \leqslant l \leqslant L$, assume that $\{X_i^{(l)}, Y_i^{(l)}\}_{1 \leqslant i \leqslant n_l}$ are generated following
\[
    X_i^{(l)} \stackrel{i . i . d}{\sim} \mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}, \quad Y_i^{(l)} \mid X_i^{(l)} \stackrel{i . i . d}{\sim} \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)} \quad \text { for } \quad i \in [n_l],
\]
where $\mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}$ denotes the distribution function of $X_i^{(l)} \in \mathbb{R}^p$, $\mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)}$ denotes the conditional distribution of the continuous outcome $Y_i^{(l)} \in \mathbb{R}$ given $X_i^{(l)}$, and $[n]=\{1, \ldots, n\}$ for any positive integer $n$. We also use $\PP\ul := \PP\ul_{X,Y}=\PP\ul_{X} \PP\ul_{Y|X}$ to denote the joint distribution for $(X,Y)$ on $l$-th source domain. To accommodate semi-supervised settings common in EHR, where observing $Y$ often requires manual annotation, we allow each source to additionally observe unlabeled samples with only covariates $X\ul_i$ observed for $n_l < i \leqslant N_l$. Suppose that the covariates $X = (A\trans,W\trans)\trans$, where $A_{q\times 1}$ denotes a vector of predictors for $Y$ with its first element being constant $1$ and $W_{(p-q)\times 1}$ denotes some auxiliary covariates that are informative for $Y$ but not included in the outcome model of our interest. In our primarily interested setup, $X$ can be high-dimensional and $A$ can be low- or high-dimensional. In summary, for each source $l \in [L]$, we observe the data $\Dsc_l =\big\{X\ul_i= (A_i\ul,W_i\ul)_{i\in [N_l]}, (Y_i\ul)_{i\in [n_l]}\big\}$.

For a potential target population, assume the covariates and outcome, denoted by $\big\{X_i^{(0)}=(A_i^{(0)},W_i^{(0)}),Y_i^{(0)}\big\}_{i\in[N_0]}$, satisfy
\[
X_i^{(0)} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} \PP_X^{(0)}, \qquad
Y_i^{(0)} \mid X_i^{(0)} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} \PP_{Y | X}^{(0)},
\qquad i\in[N_0],
\]
and we use $\PP_X^{(0)}$, $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$, and $\PP^{(0)}$ to denote, respectively, the target covariate distribution, conditional distribution, and joint distribution. Our objective is to leverage multiple source datasets to construct a predictive and generalizable linear risk model for $Y \sim A$ in the target domain, as further discussed in the following Remark~\ref{rem:1}. Beyond strong predictive performance for some specific target distribution, we pursue reliability across a range of plausible target populations. This goal is complicated by two forms of distributional shift in our data: (i) covariate shift, where $\PP_X^{(0)}$ may differ from $\{\PP_X^{(l)}\}_{l\in[L]}$; and (ii) conditional model drift, where $\PP_{Y | X}^{(0)}$ may differ from $\{\PP_{Y | X}^{(l)}\}_{l\in[L]}$. Moreover, we focus on unsupervised domain adaptation, where we observe covariates $X_i^{(0)}$ but not outcomes $Y_i^{(0)}$ in the target domain. Specifically, the available target data are $\mathcal{D}_0=\{X_i^{(0)}=(A_i^{(0)},W_i^{(0)})\}_{i\in[N_0]}.$ This setting is both practically important and technically challenging, particularly in applications such as EHR studies, where obtaining outcome labels can be costly.



\begin{remark}
Auxiliary or surrogate features $W$ have been frequently considered in literature \citep[e.g.]{xia2024prediction}. Taking EHR-linked genetic risk studies as an example, $Y$ is the primary phenotype obtained by manual chart review, $A$ is taken as genetic markers and $W$ includes EHR proxies of $Y$ such as relevant diagnostic codes and laboratory test results. Since the scientific goal is to use genes to predict disease risk, our interest is in modeling $Y\sim A$ rather than $Y\sim A,W$. Nevertheless, $W$ is not only informative to $Y$ but also a characteristic of the distributional shift between the sources and the target. Thus, including $W$ can help adjust for the distributional shifts: while the distribution of $Y\mid A$ may differ substantially across populations, further conditioning on $W$ can often reduce these discrepancies, making $Y\mid A,W$ more transferable.
\label{rem:1}
\end{remark}


% To ensure distributional robustness while preserving accuracy for future target populations similar to the observed target, we introduce a {\em joint-mixing} working assumption. This assumption enables us to derive an initial estimate of the target distribution $\mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\uz$, providing a foundation for robust model adaptation. Next, we develop the DORM estimator, designed to optimize the worst-case performance across a set of potential target distributions. This set is defined within the convex hull spanned by the estimated target distribution and the observed source distributions, ensuring robustness against distributional shifts. Figure \ref{fig: data} illustrates the data structure and approximate joint-mixing assumption to be formally introduced next.

