\subsection{Fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime}
\label{subsec:joint-mixing}
{ 
When no target outcomes $Y^{(0)}$ are available, the target conditional distribution $\PP\uz_{Y|X}$ or full distribution $\PP\uz$ are generally unidentifiable so knowledge transfer needs to be driven entirely by the observed target covariates $X^{(0)}$ and the source joints $\{\PP^{(l)}\}_{l=1}^L$. In genetic studies, genotype-phenotype pairs for an admixed cohort arise by mixing ancestral components with domain-specific ancestry proportions. In EHR, patient trajectories and outcomes are often driven by common demographics, disease subtypes or workflows. Motivated by these, we introduce a \textit{joint-mixing regime}, where we assume that the joint distribution $\PP\uz$ of covariates $X$ and outcome $Y$ on the target domain, can be well approximated by the source joint distributions $\PP\ul$.} This regime can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
    (X^{(0)},Y^{(0)}) \sim \mathbb{P}\uz:= \mathbb{P}\xz\mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\uz =\suml \rho_l^* \mathbb{P}\ul:= \suml \rho_l^* \mathbb{P}^{(l)}_{X}\mathbb{P}^{(l)}_{Y | X},
\label{eq:ideal joint}
\end{equation}  
where $\rho^*=(\rho_1^*,\ldots,\rho_L^*)$ is the set of (prior) mixing probabilities belonging to the $L$-dimensional simplex 
$
\Delta_L = \{\rho \in \mathbb{R}_L \mid \suml \rho_l = 1, \rho_l \geqslant 0 , \forall l \in [L]\}.
$
Note that (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) also implies a mixture form of the marginal distribution of $X$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbb{P}\xz=\sum_{l=1}^L \rho_l^* \mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}.
\label{eq:xmix}
\end{equation}
Let $\mathrm{d} \PP$ denote the probability density or mass function of any distribution function $\PP$, and for any $\rho\in \Delta_L$, denote the mixture density function as $\Mix(x;\rho)=\sum_{l=1}^L\rho_l \mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_X(x).$ Then under the ideal joint-mixing regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint}, we have $X_i^{(0)}\sim \Mix(x;\rho^*)$. To generate $X$ from $\Mix(x;\rho)$, one can first generate a latent variable $U\in [L]$ with $\PP(U = l)=\rho_l$ indicating the original source, and then sample $X \mid U = l \sim \mathbb{P}\xl$. 

Importantly, under the joint-mixing regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint}, the conditional distribution on the target domain $\PP_{Y|X}\uz$ is {\em no longer} identified as any marginal convex combination of the source conditional distributions considered in recent literature \citep[e.g.]{wang2025distributionally}. As shown in Proposition \ref{propo:conmodel} below, under (\ref{eq:ideal joint}), $\mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\uz$ can be fully identified from $\Dsc_l$ and $\Dsc_0$ as a posterior-weighted combination of source conditionals, even in the absence of observations of $Y^{(0)}$ in the target data.
\begin{proposition}
    \label{propo:conmodel}
    Under the joint-mixing regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint}, we have
    \begin{equation}
    \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\uz = \sum_{l=1}^L \eta_l(X;\rho^*) \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\ul
    \label{eq:y|xmix}
    \end{equation}
    where the posterior probability $\eta_l(X;\rho^*)$ is defined as
    \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:posterior}
        \eta_l (X;\rho^*):= { \mathbb{P}} (U=l\mid X)=\frac{\rho^*_l \mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_X(X)}{\sum_{k=1}^L\rho^*_k \mathrm{d} \PP^{(k)}_X(X)}.
    \end{equation}
\end{proposition}


When it comes to identifying $\rho$ from the observed data, it is natural to consider the best mixture approximation of the distribution of covariates $X^{(0)}$:
\begin{equation}
  \bar\rho= \underset{\rho \in \Delta_L}{\arg\min}\ D_{\KL}\left( \mathrm{d} \PP_X^{(0)}\mid \Mix(x;\rho) \right)=\underset{\rho \in \Delta_L}{\arg\max}\ \EE_{\PP_X^{(0)}}\log\{\Mix(X;\rho)\},
\label{eq:kldiv}
\end{equation}
where $D_{\KL}(\cdot\mid\cdot)$ is Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence. Under regularity assumptions to be introduced in Section \ref{sec:theory}, (\ref{eq:kldiv}) is a strictly convex problem with a unique solution no matter (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) holds or not; when (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) holds, we have $\bar\rho=\rho^*$ and $\Mix(x;\bar\rho)=\PP_X^{(0)}$. Under the joint-mixing regime (\ref{eq:ideal joint}), the target distribution can be identified as the following distribution
\begin{equation}
    \Msc_{\mathrm{C}} = \Big(\mathbb{P}\xz, \sum_{l=1}^L \eta_l(X;\bar\rho) \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\ul\Big),
    \label{eq:joint dist}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{\rho}$ is defined in (\ref{eq:kldiv}). In this situation, the distribution of $Y\mid X$ on target is fully ``coupled'' with the posterior weights $\eta_l(X;\bar\rho)$ induced by the joint-mixing structure. Thus, we name it as \textit{fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime}.

To fit linear models, we introduce reward function $R_{\PP} (\beta) = \mathbb{E}_{(X, Y) \sim \PP} \left[Y^2-(Y-{ A\trans \beta})^2 \right]$ that measures the variation of $Y$ explained by $A\trans\beta$ when $(X,Y)\sim\PP$. Under the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime with our identified $\Msc_{\mathrm{C}}$, it is natural to obtain the risk model coefficients $\beta\in\mathbb{R}^q$ by maximizing the reward function $R_{\PP} (\beta)$ on $\Msc_{\mathrm{C}}$:
\begin{equation}
\bar{\beta}_{\mix}=\underset{\beta\in\mathbb{R}^q}{\arg\max}\ R_{\PP \in \Msc_{\mathrm{C}}} (\beta).
\label{eq:least:sq:mix}
\end{equation}
%which maximizes the reward under the unique target distribution in $\Msc_{\mathrm{C}}$.
%We will also discuss the choice reward function in Remark \ref{remark:reward} in the following Section \ref{subsec:partial}.

% {\darkred Here we target the best linear predictor of $Y$ given $A$, even the true $\EE(Y\mid A)$ arises from a posterior mixture. This linear model preserves interpretability in a lot of real biomedical studies. Moreover, despite a linear least squares model, features $A$ can include spline bases, interactions, or learned embeddings, leading to flexible model capacity.}  


\subsection{Partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime}
\label{subsec:partial}

The fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime posits that the joint distribution of $(X,Y)$ of target can be well approximated by a mixture of source joint distributions. %In practice, this assumption may fail. For example,
In multi-institution EHR settings, the joint law of $(X,Y)$ is often shaped by site-level selection, local environments, patient compliance, and documentation practices. Such factors can distort the conditional generating mechanism of $Y$ in ways that break exact joint-mixture structure: the mixture weights governing $Y\mid X$ do not fully coincide with those implied by $X$. Consequently, the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime is not guaranteed to hold.

Motivated by this, we propose a unified framework called \emph{partial $(X,Y)$-coupling} between covariate shift ($\PP_X$) and conditional drift ($\PP_{Y | X}$). Recall that equation~\eqref{eq:joint dist} corresponds to the unique distribution identified under the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime. At the other extreme, if we assumed the target covariate distribution $\PP_X\uz$ carries no information about the target conditional distribution, we would come to the \textit{fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled} regime. This endpoint has been considered in related works like \cite{wang2025distributionally}, where the target conditional varies over the entire simplex spanned by the source conditionals. Accordingly, the fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled distribution set can be written as
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}_{\rm DC}
:=\left\{\left(\mathbb{P}\uz_X, \mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}\right): \mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}=\sum_{l=1}^L \delta_l \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)}, \ \delta \in \Delta_L\right\},
\label{eq:fully decouple}
\end{equation}
which is large and typically leads to overly permissive results since $\delta$ is unconstrained or not identifiable from the covariates on the target domain.

% {\color{red} Need to explain the mixture-coupled regime more clearly.}

% {\color{red} This sentence is a bit long and not easy to follow:} The joint–mixing regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint} provides an identified starting point: from $\PP^{(0)}_X$ we obtain reference weights $\bar\rho$ by projecting onto the source hull and define a coupled reference conditional through posterior-weighted average of source conditionals. This actually corresponds to the \emph{fully coupled} endpoint of the mixture-coupling spectrum, where the target conditional is fully determined by $\PP^{(0)}_X$ via joint mixing structure. In contrast, when $Y$ is unobserved, {\color{red} May not need to introduce Maximin here as we have not introduced DRO yet. Just introduce the ``conditional mixing" regime and say the mixing weights are not identifiable without target labels:} conditional group DRO (Maximin) \citep{guo2022statistical,wang2025distributionally} adopts the \emph{fully decoupled} endpoint, by allowing the target conditional to range over the entire simplex of source conditionals, ignoring mixture structure in $X$. The uncertainty set of Maximin usually can be written as $\mathcal{M}_{\sf CG}
% :=\left\{\left(\mathbb{P}\uz_X, \mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}\right): \mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}=\sum_{l=1}^L \delta_l \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)}, \ \delta \in \Delta_L\right\},$ which is often conservative because $\delta$ is not informed by the target covariates. 



The \textit{partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime} is a unified framework integrating the fully coupled and fully decoupled endpoints, achieved by decomposing the target conditional into a coupled piece identified from the joint-mixing regime and an unidentifiable decoupled part. Formally, DORM considers the following uncertainty set for target domain distribution:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}\left(\smax\right)=\left\{ \left(\PP\xz,\mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}(s,\delta)\right):{ \delta \in \Delta_L},~s \in [0,\smax]\right\},
\label{eq:uncertainty}
\end{equation}
where the potential target distributions are formulated as
\begin{equation}
    \mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}(s,\delta)= \sum_{l=1}^L \big[ (1-s)\eta_l(X;\bar\rho) + s\delta_l \big]\mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)},
    \label{eq:Y|Xdist}
\end{equation}
and $\eta_l(X;\bar\rho)$ is defined in \eqref{eq:posterior}, reflecting the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime. Here $s\in[0,1]$ admits a natural probabilistic interpretation: for each $(X,Y)$ draw, with probability $1-s$ the conditional follows the fully {coupled} reference mixture $\sum_l \eta_l(X;\bar\rho)\,\PP^{(l)}_{Y | X}$, and with probability $s$ it follows a decoupled mixture $\sum_l \delta_l \PP^{(l)}_{Y | X}$ that is ``orthogonal'' to the distribution of $X$ on target. The hyperparameter $s_{\max}$, serving as the \textit{decoupling budget}, limits how much probability mass is allowed to deviate from full coupling. In specific, taking $s_{\max}=0$ collapses \eqref{eq:Y|Xdist} to the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled $\Msc_{\mathrm{C}}$ in~\eqref{eq:joint dist}; $s_{\max}=1$ recovers the fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled regime in~\eqref{eq:fully decouple}; intermediate $s_{\max}$ delivers \emph{partial $(X,Y)$-coupling}, leveraging information in $X$ through $\eta(\cdot;\bar\rho)$ while allowing departures through the decoupled component. Moreover, if we adjust for some ``pre-mixing'' variables in $X$ that are not likely to be embedded in the mixture structure, the covariate and conditional outcome distributions are more likely to be coupled on the target domain; see more details in Section~\ref{sec:complicated}.

% \begin{remark}
% In multi-institution EHRs, the marginal $\PP_X$ is shaped by site-level selection and documentation: demographics and insurance, referral, healthcare utilization, and coding intensity all perturb $\PP_X$ in ways that do not necessarily govern outcomes. Consequently, the conditional mixture on the target aligns with, but need not exactly equal, the mixture implied by $X$; DORM captures this by allocating an adversarial fraction $s$ to such unidentifiable deviations while regimeing the remainder $1-s$ to the coupled, physiology-driven reference. 
% \end{remark}

%where the first term in $\mathbb{T}_{Y \mid X}(y;s,\delta)$ corresponds to the conditional mixture distribution of $Y$ implied by (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) and (\ref{eq:y|xmix}), representing our best approximation of target $\PP\uz_{Y|X}$ in the ideal joint-mixing scenario. By assigning a large proportion \(1-s\) to this mixture, we capture the intuition that (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) is our primary working assumption. The second term is a marginal mixture of source conditional distributions weighted by \(s\), where \(\delta=(\delta_1,\ldots,\delta_L)\) resides in the probability simplex to encode adversarial weights across sources \(l=1,\ldots,L\). Conceptually, this term allows part of the target distribution to deviate arbitrarily from our best guess, ensuring robustness against potential misspecifications and enhancing generalizability for various target domains. Here, $\smax$ is a hyper-parameter controlling the upper range of $s$, i.e., our trust in assumption (\ref{eq:ideal joint}), which will be discussed in more details later. 

Then, we derive a distributionally robust predictor under this partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime by optimizing the
worst-case predictive performance over the partially identified set of distributions in \eqref{eq:uncertainty}. We define the population level DORM regression coefficients as
\begin{equation}
\barbetare(\smax) :=\underset{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^q}{\arg \max } \min _{\PP \in \uncer} R_{\PP}(\beta),
\label{eq:droY}
\end{equation}
where the reward function $R_{\PP}(\beta):=\mathbb{E}_{(X, Y) \sim \PP}\left[Y^2-(Y-{ A\trans \beta})^2\right]$. It can be viewed as a two-sided game that one agent searches over $\uncer$ to find the most adverse target distribution $\PP$ for $\beta$ within decoupling budget $\smax$, and another agent updates $\beta$ to maximize the reward for such an unfavorable target population. Different from most existing domain adaptation methods like \cite{li2022transfer} and \cite{xiong2023distributionally}, solving (\ref{eq:droY}) does not rely on any observations of $Y^{(0)}$ on the target. For the choice of the reward function $R_{\PP}(\beta)$, \cite{wang2025distributionally} provides comparison of different $R_{\PP}(\beta)$ in the context of group adversarial learning.

% \begin{remark} \label{remark:reward}
% Choice on the reward function $R_{\mathbb{P}}(\beta)$ is diverse in various studies. \cite{agarwal22b} and
% \cite{mo2024minimax} frame their reward function as a regret, measuring the excess risk of the model compared to the optimal model for the distribution $\PP$. \cite{xiong2023distributionally} compared the mean squared loss of the model $\beta$ to that of the initial estimator $\beta_{\operatorname{init}}$ constructed using labeled target sample. \cite{wang2025distributionally} provided an evaluation of different reward function choices in the context of group adversarial learning, asserting that the reward function $R_{\mathbb{P}}(\beta)$ employed in our DORM framework is both independent of noise levels for source domains and computationally feasible when incorporating general convex prior mixture information.
% \end{remark}

The decoupling budget $\smax$ in (\ref{eq:droY}) encodes a trade-off on the degree of adversary for $\barbetare(\smax)$ and $1-\smax$ carries one's confidence on the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime. The smaller $\smax$ gets, the smaller $\Msc (\smax)$ is, and the closer $\barbetare(\smax)$ will be to $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ that works under the fully coupled case (\ref{eq:ideal joint}). When $\smax=0$, we have $\barbetare(\smax)=\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ without robustness to any adversarial distributions departing from fully coupled joint-mixing (\ref{eq:ideal joint}). On the other hand, a larger $\smax$ results in a larger uncertainty set more likely to contain the actual target $\mathbb{P}\uz$ and produces a more robust model. When $\smax = 1$, $\barbetare(\smax)$ will become a covariate-shift-adjusted maximin model similar to \cite{guo2022statistical}. %We will also briefly discuss potential tuning strategies of $\smax$ in Section \ref{sec:tuning}.
%and study the impact of $\smax$ in both theoretical and numerical studies.  

% \begin{remark}
%      It is noteworthy that $\bar\beta_{\mix}$ is not a marginal mixture of each source model, because the $Y\mid X$ distribution $\sum_{l=1}^L \eta_l(X;\rho) \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\ul$ in (\ref{eq:least:sq:mix}) is weighted by posterior weights which depend on $X$ rather than constant weights. Figure \ref{fig: flowchart 1} presents two different scenarios for $\bar\beta_\mix$. In the first scenario where $\bar\beta_\mix$ is outside the convex hull of sources, the uncertainty set for $Y\mid X$ conditional model in (\ref{eq:Y|Xdist}) is a convex combination of each source conditional and the mixture conditional. In the second scenario when $\bar\beta_{\mix}$ is already in the convex hull of source models, the uncertainty set for $Y\mid X$ is essentially a convex combination of source conditional models.
% \end{remark}


% \begin{figure}[htb]
%     \centering
%     \includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{Pictures/flowchart_solo.pdf}
%     \caption{\footnotesize Geometric illustration of DORM uncertainty sets $\uncer$ (shaded area) and the corresponding solution $\barbetare(\smax)$ (colored dots) of (\ref{eq:droY}) with five different $\smax$ values. The left subplot shows the case when $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ (which represents the conditional mixture model) lies outside the convex hull spanned by the four sources, while the right represents $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ inside the source hull.}
%     \label{fig: flowchart 1}
% \end{figure}

\subsection{DORM identification}
\label{sec:ident}

We next characterize the solution of the maximin problem in (\ref{eq:droY}). The following theorem derives an explicit solution of (\ref{eq:droY}) as a mixture of some {coupled} joint-mixing coefficients and {decoupled} group-wise coefficients, with the decoupling budget $s_{\max}$ enforcing a minimum weight on the coupled part.

\begin{theorem}
The solution to population DORM problem in \eqref{eq:droY} can be identified as
\begin{equation}
        \barbetare(\smax) = \sum_{l=1}^{L} \gamma^*_l \bar{\beta}_l + \gamma^*_{\mix} \bar{\beta}_{\mix} \quad \text{with} \quad \gamma^* = \underset{\gamma \in \mathcal{S}(\smax)}{\arg \min } \gamma\trans \Gamma \gamma,
    \label{eq:idenPopu}
\end{equation}
where $\gamma = (\gamma_1,\cdots,\gamma_L,\gamma_{\mix}),\ \mathcal{S}(\smax) = \left\{\gamma \mid \gamma \in \Delta_{L+1}, \gamma_{\mix} \in [1-\smax,1] \right\}$, $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ is defined in (\ref{eq:least:sq:mix}), and $\bar{\beta}_l= {\arg\min}_{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^q}\ \EE_{(X,Y) \sim (\PP_X^{(0)},\PP_{Y \mid X}\ul)}\left(Y-A\trans \beta\right)^2,l\in[L].$
% \begin{equation}
%     \bar{\beta}_l=  \underset{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^q}{\arg\min}\ \EE_{(X,Y) \sim (\PP_X^{(0)},\PP_{Y \mid X}\ul)}\left(Y-A\trans \beta\right)^2, \quad l\in[L].
%     \label{eq:Popuql}
% \end{equation}
The matrix $\Gamma=(\Gamma_{l,k})_{l,k \in [L+1]}$ is defined by $\Gamma_{l,k}=\bar{\beta}_l\trans \bar\Sigma\uz \bar{\beta}_k$ with $\bar\beta_{L+1}:=\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$, and $\bar\Sigma\uz=\EE_{\PP_X^{(0)}} AA\trans$. 
\label{thm:PopuIdenti}
\end{theorem}
By Theorem \ref{thm:PopuIdenti}, \(\barbetare(\smax)\) is a convex combination of \(\bar{\beta}_l\) (\(l \in [L]\)) and \(\bar{\beta}_{\mix}\). Each \(\bar{\beta}_l\) is obtained by a population-level least squares fit of \(Y\sim A\) under the hypothetical distribution $(\PP_X^{(0)},\PP_{Y \mid X}\ul)$. Meanwhile, \(\bar{\beta}_{\mix}\) corresponds to the least squares solution under the mixture $(\PP_X^{(0)}, \sum_{l=1}^L \eta_l(X;\bar\rho) \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}\ul)$. Different from \cite{meinshausen2015maximin} and \cite{guo2022statistical}, our framework permits misspecification of the linear model \(Y \sim A\), a flexibility accommodated by the semiparametric approach to be introduced in Section~\ref{sec:method:est}.

The vector of weights \(\gamma^*\) in \eqref{eq:idenPopu}  is a reparameterization of $(\delta,s)$ in \eqref{eq:uncertainty}, and it is solved by a constrained quadratic optimization that balances these candidate coefficient vectors through the matrix \(\Gamma\). Notably, \(\gamma_{\mix}^*\ge 1 - \smax\) enforces that the final estimator always assigns a non-trivial weight to  \(\bar{\beta}_{\mix}\), reflecting trust in the joint-mixing model, while allowing adversarial reweighting among group-wise alternatives. %This represents a principled way to model the partial coupled target distribution, as well as hedge against potential deviation from the ideal joint-mixing fully coupled model. 
This construction yields a robust and interpretable estimator that interpolates between the estimator obtained under the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime and its decoupled adversarially reweighted alternatives.

%thereby enhancing predictive reliability in heterogeneous and partially misspecified settings. 
%Figure \ref{fig: flowchart 1} illustrates the uncertainty set in (\ref{eq:droY}) and demonstrates the solutions given by Theorem \ref{thm:PopuIdenti}.

%Different from results in \cite{guo2022statistical}, \cite{xiong2023distributionally}, we don't need to assume a linear model on the source sites. Instead we can fit any imputation model for $m_l(x)$ including linear model. In our theorem we also have an mixture effect term $\gamma^*_{L+1} \bar{\beta}_{L+1}$. The larger the $\gamma^*_{L+1}$, the closer it aligns with our assumptions about the mixed target joint distribution. Consequently, the maximin solution $\betare$ becomes closer to the linear coefficient $\bar{\beta}_{L+1}$  which is a mixed effect according to the joint distribution's mixture proportions, which couldn't be attained by previous results.

