\section{Estimation procedures of DORM}\label{sec:method:est}
\subsection{Double machine learning estimation}

Let $\bar\eta_l(x)=\eta_l(x;\bar\rho)$, $\cpzh = N_0\inv \sum_{i=1}^{N_0}$ be the empirical mean operator on the target data $\Dsc_0$ and $\cplh = n_l\inv \sum_{i=1}^{n_l}$ denote the mean on the labeled sample from source $l$. 
%For $u=(u_1,\ldots,u_d)\trans \in \mathbb{R}^d$, we define its $\ell_r$ norm as $\|u\|_r=\big(\sum_{j=1}^d|u_j|^r\big)^{1 / r}$ for any $r > 0$. 
Following Theorem \ref{thm:PopuIdenti}, the key step in finite sample implementation is to estimate coefficients $\bar{\beta}_l$ for $l\in[L+1]$ where $\bar{\beta}_{L+1}=\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$. Here we use $L+1$  for mathematical convenience in expressing vectors and matrices.
According to their definition, we have
\begin{equation}
    \bar{\beta}_l =(\bar\Sigma\uz)^{-1} \EE_0 \bar{m}_l(X) A,~l\in[L]; \quad\bar{\beta}_{\mix} =(\bar\Sigma\uz)^{-1} \suml \EE_0 \bar\eta_l(X)\bar{m}_l(X) A: = \bar{\beta}_{L+1},
    \label{eq:betabar}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{m}_l(x) = \EE_{\PP_{Y \mid X}\ul}(Y\mid X = x)$ is the conditional mean of $Y\mid X$ on source $l$. Suppose that we already obtain the estimators $\mlh$ and $\elh$ for the nuisance functions $\bar{m}_l$ and $\bar{\eta}_l$ using general learning methods like parametric regression and modern machine learning tools, the specific procedure of which will be introduced in Section \ref{sec:method:est:nuis}. Then for low-dimensional regression of $Y\sim A$, we can derive the plug-in estimators as:
\begin{equation}
\footnotesize 
    \widetilde{\beta}_l = (\szh)\inv \cpzh  \mlh(X_i\uz) A_i\uz, ~l \in [L]; \quad\widetilde{\beta}_{\mix} = (\szh)\inv  \suml \cpzh\elh(X_i\uz)  \mlh(X_i\uz) A_i\uz :=\widetilde{\beta}_{L+1},
    \label{eq:btil}
\end{equation}
where $\szh = \cpzh A\uz_i (A\uz_i)\trans$. Nevertheless, such $\widetilde{\beta}_l$'s may suffer from large bias due to the potential misspecification or excessive estimation errors in $\mlh$, especially when it is obtained with a relatively small labeled sample with the size $n_l$. Inspired by the doubly robust \citep{bang2005doubly} and double machine learning (DML) \citep{chernozhukov2016double} frameworks, we propose to correct the bias incurred by $\mlh-\bar{m}_l$ through the augmented estimators:
\begin{align}
    \qlh & = \widetilde{\beta}_l + \cplh \wlh(X^{(l)}_i) [Y^{(l)}_i-\mlh(X^{(l)}_i)] (\szh)^{-1} A\ul_i,\quad\forall~l \in [L], \label{eq:qlhat} \\
    \widehat{\beta}_{\mix} & = \widetilde{\beta}_{\mix} + \suml \cplh \elh(X\ul_i) \wlh(X^{(l)}_i) [Y^{(l)}_i-\mlh(X^{(l)}_i)] (\szh)^{-1} A\ul_i := \ph, \label{eq:ql+1hat}
\end{align}
where $\wlh(x)$ is an estimator of the density ratio between the target and source $l$: $\bar{w}_l(x) = \mathrm{d} \PP\xz(x)/\mathrm{d}\PP\xl(x)$ obtained using general learning methods. For high-dimensional $A$, we can naturally extend the DML construction to a regularized regression version with penalties like ridge or Lasso. See the detailed forms in Appendix \ref{sec:app:regularize}.


% {
% \color{blue} A doubly robust construction. Define that
% \[
% \widehat{R}_{\Mix}=\suml \widehat{\rho}^{\dagger}_l\cplh \widehat{w}^{\dagger}(X^{(l)}_i)A^{(l)}_i\Big(Y^{(l)}_i-\sum_{k=1}^L\widehat{\eta}_k(X^{(l)}_i)\widehat{m}_k(X^{(l)}_i) \Big),
% \]
% where $\widehat{\rho}^{\dagger}$ needs to be a debiased estimator for $\bar\rho$ with parametric convergence rate, and $\widehat{w}^{\dagger}(x)=1/(\suml \widehat{\rho}^{\dagger}_l/\wlh(x))$ is actually the density ratio between the target and the mixture of sources. Then we construct:
% \[
% \widehat{\beta}_{L+1} = (\szh)\inv\Big[\suml \cpzh\elh(X_i\uz)  \mlh(X_i\uz) A_i\uz+\widehat{R}_{\Mix}\Big].
% \]
% The idea is to view the source sample mixture (with weights $\bar\rho_l$) as a new source population. The conditional mean model of $Y$ on this population is estimated by $\suml \cpzh\elh(X_i\uz)  \mlh(X_i\uz)$ and the density ratio is given by $\widehat{w}^{\dagger}$. Thus, we need a debiased estimation of $\bar\rho_l$ to make the empirical version of it accurate enough.

% }


Essentially, $\beta_l$'s are parameters defined on some hypothetical (counterfactual) populations without actual samples due to covariate shift. Thus, our case falls into the semiparametric estimation problem frequently studied in the contexts of missing data and causal inference. Inspired by existing semiparametric literature \citep[e.g.]{robins1994estimation}, we establish in Proposition \ref{propo:Doubly} the doubly robust property of $\qlh$ with respect to the two sets of nuisance models $w_l$ and $m_l$ for $l\in[L+1]$.
\begin{proposition}
\label{propo:Doubly}
Denote by $\qlh = \qlh(\wlh,\mlh), l \in [L]$ and $\widehat{\beta}_{\mix} = \widehat{\beta}_{\mix}(\elh,\wlh,\mlh)$ in (\ref{eq:qlhat}) and (\ref{eq:ql+1hat}). We have that $\qlh(w_l,m_l)$ is consistent for $ \bar{\beta}_l$ and $ \widehat{\beta}_{\mix}(\bar{\eta}_l,w_l,m_l)$ is consistent for $\bar{\beta}_{L+1}$ when either $w_l = \bar{w}_l$ or $m_l = \bar{m}_l$ holds for every $l \in [L]$.
\end{proposition}

Proposition \ref{propo:Doubly} implies that our constructions in (\ref{eq:qlhat}) and (\ref{eq:ql+1hat}) are less sensitive and doubly robust to excessive errors in the machine learners for density ratio model $w_l$ and the conditional mean model $m_l$. In our primary setup with the semi-supervised structure $N_l\gg n_l$ and larger source samples $N_l\gg N_0$ for $l\in[L]$, our estimation procedure of $\eta_l$ to be introduced in Section \ref{sec:method:est:nuis} can include larger samples for machine learning and, thus, produce an $\elh$ converging substantially faster than $\wlh$ and $\mlh$ when these models are of similar complexity. More detailed and rigorous quantification of this fact will be given in Section \ref{sec:theory}.
%\begin{remark}
%Note that such a robustness property in Proposition \ref{propo:Doubly} does not apply to $\elh$, even though (\ref{eq:qlhat}) and (\ref{eq:ql+1hat}) are already in the semiparametric efficient forms under our setting. Meanwhile, in our primary setup with the semi-supervised structure $N_l\gg n_l$ and the small target sample $N_l\gg N_0$ for each $l$, our estimation procedure of $\eta_l$ to be introduced in Section \ref{sec:method:est:nuis} can typically produce an estimator $\elh$ converging substantially faster than $\wlh$ and $\mlh$ when these models are of similar complexity and estimated using similar learning methods. One can find more details in Theorem \ref{thm:betarate}.
%\end{remark}
After obtaining $\widehat{\beta}_l$ for $l\in[L+1]$, we can directly use Theorem \ref{thm:PopuIdenti} to derive the DORM estimator with some pre-specified $\smax$. In specific, we compute $\widehat\Gamma=(\widehat\Gamma_{l,k})_{l,k \in [L+1]}$ with $\widehat\Gamma_{l,k}=\widehat{\beta}_l\trans \widehat\Sigma\uz \widehat{\beta}_k$ and $\widehat\Sigma\uz=\cpzh A^{(0)}(A^{(0)})\trans$, then solve the quadratic programming problem for the adversarial weights $\widehat{\gamma}= \arg\min_{\gamma \in \mathcal{S}(\smax)} \gamma\trans\widehat{\Gamma}\gamma$ and obtain $\ours(\smax) = \sum_{l=1}^{L+1}\glh \qlh $. 

Estimating the nuisance functions in (\ref{eq:btil}), (\ref{eq:qlhat}) and (\ref{eq:ql+1hat}) is not a straightforward application of machine learning considering the source-mixture structure and the relatively small size of the target data compared to the sources. Next, we propose a novel pipeline for efficient estimation of $\bar{\eta}_l$, $\bar{w}_l$ and $\bar{m}_l$ allowing the use of general machine learning methods. 





\subsection{Estimation of nuisance models}\label{sec:method:est:nuis}

The conditional mean model estimator $\mlh$ can be obtained in a straightforward way, regressing $Y\ul\sim X\ul$ on the $n_l$ labeled sample in source $l$, using arbitrary learning methods such as random forest, and neural networks. To estimate $\bar{\eta}_l$ in (\ref{eq:y|xmix}) with unknown $\bar\rho_l$ defined by (\ref{eq:kldiv}), one may consider first estimating each $\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_X$ for $l\in[L]$, then plugging them into the empirical version of (\ref{eq:kldiv}) on the target sample to estimate $\bar\rho_l$, and using the estimators of $\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_X$ and $\bar\rho_l$ for construction. However, this procedure may result in poor accuracy due to the common difficulty in estimating potentially high-dimensional density functions like $\PP^{(l)}_X$ \citep{gretton2009covariate}. To avoid this issue, our idea is to leverage the fact that
\begin{equation}
\bar\eta_l(x)=\frac{\bar\rho_l \bar{r}_l(x)}{\sum_{k=1}^L\bar\rho_k \bar{r}_k(x)};\quad   \bar\rho= \max_{\rho \in \Delta_L}\EE_{\PP_X^{(0)}}\log\Big(\sum_{l=1}^L \rho_l \bar{r}_l(X)\Big),    
\label{eq:tildedensityratio}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{r}_l(x)$ is some density ratio function
\begin{equation}
    \bar{r}_l(x):=\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}(x)}{\mathrm{d} \PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}(x)} =  \frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(0)}(x)}{\bar{w}_l(x) \mathrm{d} \PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}(x)},\quad l\in[L],
    \label{eq:barrl}
\end{equation}
and $\PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}$ is an arbitrary reference distribution with its domain covering each source $l$ and will be specified later. Based on (\ref{eq:tildedensityratio}), we can replace the need in estimating $\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_X$ with $\bar{r}_l(x)$, which can be converted to a classification problem. In specific, for each $l \in[L]$, we merge $\{X_i^{(l)}\}_{i \in [N_l]}$ with samples from the reference distribution $\{X_i^{(\operatorname{ref})}\}$ and denote an observation randomly drawn from this pooled data set as $\tilde{X}_i^{(l)}$. Then define a response $G_i^{(l)} \in\{0,1\}$ such that $G_i^{(l)}=1$ if $\tilde{X}_i^{(l)}$ is actually from source $l$ and $G_i^{(l)}=0$ if $\widetilde{X}_i^{(l)}$ is from the reference data set. Then we have $\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}(x)=\mathrm{d} \PP(x \mid G_i^{(l)}=1)$ and $\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(\operatorname{ref})}_X(x)=\mathrm{d} \PP (x \mid G_i^{(l)}=0)$ and that
\begin{equation}
    \bar{r}_l(x)=\frac{\PP(G_i^{(l)}=0)}{\PP (G_i^{(l)}=1)} \frac{\PP(G_i^{(l)}=1 \mid \tilde{X}_i^{(l)}=x)}{\PP(G_i^{(l)}=0 \mid \tilde{X}_i^{(l)}=x)}.
\label{eq:densityratio}
\end{equation}
In (\ref{eq:densityratio}), $\PP (G_i^{(l)}=0)/\PP (G_i^{(l)}=1) $ can be approximated by the sample size ratio between the reference data and source $l$, and $\PP (G_i^{(l)}=1 \mid \tilde{X}_i^{(l)}=x)$ can be estimated using general machine learning methods such as logistic Lasso and random forest classifier on the full source samples with sizes $N_l$'s. When $\PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}$ is properly specified, such a classification task is typically much easier to implement and has more accuracy compared to the direct estimation of density $\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(l)}(x)$. %Alternatively, one could also estimate $\bar{r}_l$ using covariate balancing approaches such as \cite{gretton2009covariate} and \cite{imai2014covariate}. 
For the sake of estimation efficiency, in practice the reference sample $\{X_i^{(\operatorname{ref})}\}$ can be taken as either (i) the source site with the largest sample size or (ii) the pool of all source samples, to maximize the size of training data.
% \begin{remark}
% For the sake of estimation efficiency, the reference sample $\{X_i^{(\operatorname{ref})}\}$ can be taken as either (i) the source site with the largest sample size or (ii) the pool of all source samples, to maximize the size of training data. Choice (ii) also ensures sufficient overlap between $\PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}$ and every $\PP_X^{(l)}$ and, consequently, more stable training with general machine learning. Empirical estimation under choice (ii) can be realized by randomly splitting each $\Dsc_l$ into two sets with certain proportions, pooling one of them together for $l\in[L]$ to form the reference data, and learning $\bar{r}_l(x)$ by classifying the other set versus the pooled reference data. 
% \end{remark}

With the estimator $\widehat{r}_l(x)$, we can then estimate $\rho$ through
\begin{equation}
    \widehat{\rho} = \underset{\rho \in \Delta_L}{\arg\max}\ \cpzh \log\Big(\sum_{l=1}^L\rho_l \widehat{r}_l(X)\Big)+\lambda\|\rho\|_2^2,
\label{eq:kldiv-est}
\end{equation}
and obtain the posterior weights as 
\begin{equation}
    \elh(x) = \frac{\widehat{\rho}_l{\widehat{r_l}(x)}}{\sum_{k=1}^L \widehat{\rho}_k\widehat{r}_k(x)}.
\label{eq:etalhat}
\end{equation}
In (\ref{eq:kldiv-est}), the ridge penalty on $\rho$ is introduced with a small $\lambda$ to secure a unique and stable solution when some sources $l$ and $k$ have extremely close density functions of $X$ and highly correlated $\widehat{r}_{l}(X)$ and $\widehat{r}_{k}(X)$ on the target sample. Then for the density ratio $\bar{w}_l$ between source $l$ and target, we can use a similar procedure as introduced above to obtain a generic machine learning estimate $\widehat{r}_0(x)$ of ${\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(0)}(x)}/{\mathrm{d} \PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}(x)}$ with the target and reference samples, and take each $\widehat{w}_l(x)=\widehat{r}_0(x)/\widehat{r_l}(x)$. Inspired by \cite{chernozhukov2016double}, we also use cross-fitting in our framework to remove excessive bias caused by the complicated ML estimation of the nuisance models. For simplicity, notations related to this procedure are omitted in the main paper with the complete details presented in Appendix \ref{sec:app:cross-details}. 

% we provide two options on its estimation. The first one is to use a similar procedure as introduced above to obtain a general machine learning estimate $\widehat{r}_0(x)$ of ${\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}_X^{(0)}(x)}/{d \PP_X^{(\operatorname{ref})}(x)}$ with the target and reference sample, and take each $\widehat{w}_l(x)=\widehat{r}_0(x)/\widehat{r_l}(x)$. When the target has a relatively small sample size $N_0$ compared to the sources, the error of $\widehat{w}_l$ tends to be dominated by $\widehat{r}_0(x)$ and the small $N_0$. 


% This motivates us to propose an alternative option by trusting the mixture form of $\PP_X^{(0)}$ in (\ref{eq:xmix}) and taking advantage of the mediating results in estimating $\widehat{\eta}_l$. In specific, one could use the mixture of density ratio $\sum_{l=1}^L\widehat\rho_l \widehat{r}_l(x)$ fitted from (\ref{eq:kldiv-est}) to approximate $\widehat{r}_0(x)$ and again take $\widehat{w}_l(x)=\widehat{r}_0(x)/\widehat{r_l}(x)$. This strategy can alleviate the small $\Dsc_0$ issue because given $\widehat{r_l}(x)$ estimated using the relatively large source data sets, (\ref{eq:kldiv-est}) is an $M$-estimation problem only involving $L$ parameters in $\rho$ rather than the complex models for $X$, which typically attains a parametric convergence rate with respect to the sample size $N_0$; see Lemma \ref{lemma:eta} for more details. However, this approach is subject to potential bias caused by the misspecification of (\ref{eq:xmix}), which is not an issue of our first option.




% For all the sources $l\in[L]$, we randomly partition $\Dsc_l$ into two disjoint subsets $\mathcal{A}_l$ and $\mathcal{B}_l$ with equal size, and construct two sets of estimators $\{\wlha,~\elha,~\mlha:l\in[L]\}$ and $\{\wlhb,~\elhb,~\mlhb:l\in[L]\}$ separately using $\Asc=\cup_{l=1}^L\mathcal{A}_l$ and $\Bsc=\cup_{l=1}^L\mathcal{B}_l$, with the whole target sample $\Dsc_0$ used for both sets. Denote the sub-sample empirical operators on each $l\in[L]$ as $\cplha = |\Asc_l|\inv \sum_{i \in \Asc_l}$ and $\cplhb = |\Bsc_l|\inv \sum_{i \in \Bsc_l}$. Then we construct $\qlha$ for $l\in[L+1]$ by plugging $\cplha$ and $\{\wlhb,~\elhb,~\mlhb\}$ into (\ref{eq:btil}), (\ref{eq:qlhat}), and (\ref{eq:ql+1hat}), and $\qlhb$ plugging in $\cplhb$ and $\{\wlha,~\elha,~\mlha\}$. At last, we separately combine the two sets of estimators $\qlha$'s and $\qlhb$'s with the full sample $\widehat\Sigma\uz$ to derive the corresponding adversarial weights $\glha$'s and $\glhb$'s following Theorem \ref{thm:PopuIdenti}, and output $\ours(\smax) = \sum_{l=1}^{L+1} (\glha \qlha + \glhb \qlhb)/2$ as the final DORM estimator.

%\begin{remark}{\red (Privacy Preserving Algorithm)}.
%Algorithm 1 does not require the sharing of the $l$-th source site's data $\{(X_i^{(l)}, Y_i^{(l)})\}_{i \in[n_l]}$ to other source sites or the target site. The density ratio estimation step requires transmitting the reference covariates to each source group. However, in scenarios where the density ratios are known, such as in the no covariate shift setting, the need for target covariates transmission is eliminated as well. Our proposed algorithm protects data privacy since it mainly requires the trained prediction and the density ratio model from each source data instead of the raw data. It is compiled with the data-privacy regulations such as the HIPPA Privacy Rule [Topaloglu et al., 2021] in the United States, which protects patient information and prohibits sharing patient-level data between sites.


\subsection{Tuning of decoupling budget with side information}\label{sec:tuning}

The hyper-parameter decoupling budget $\smax$ plays an important role in DORM as it controls the size of the uncertainty set $\Msc(\smax)$ and the degree of adversarial decoupling. Usually, choosing a relatively small $\smax$ (says $0.1$) to ensure enough weights on the source-mixing estimator $\widehat{\beta}_{\mix}$ is highly recommended when the joint-mixing regime (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) is reasonable. 
%e.g., our real-world application targeting mixed ethnicity subgroups. 
Moreover, when there is some side information about outcome $Y^{(0)}$ on the target, we can potentially use it to find a good choice of $\smax$. 
%We shall make some discussions here and further justify them in both theoretical and numerical studies. 

% {\color{red} May also use another notation to replace $n_0$? We could say $(X_i^\dagger,Y_i^\dagger)$ is one or more dataset potentially from the target domain (a class of distribution). For example, comes from xxx, refer to previous T, or (28)}

Suppose there is a small set of labeled data $(X_i^\dagger,Y_i^\dagger)$ for $i \in [n_\dagger]$ where $n_\dagger$ could be much smaller than both $N_0$ and $n_l$'s. The labeled data used for tuning could come from another similar study or from multiple institutions, which is allowed to be moderately different from the target $(X\uz,Y\uz) \sim \PP\uz$. In specific, $(X_i^\dagger,Y_i^\dagger) \sim \PP^\dagger$ can be some distribution in the previous uncertainty set $\uncer$ in (\ref{eq:uncertainty}), or with some contamination part as in (\ref{eq:contam1}). With such a limited sample size frequently encountered in practice, a potentially high-dimensional regression for $Y_i^\dagger\sim A_i^\dagger$ may not be tractable. However, we can use these labeled samples for the tuning of $\smax$, which tends to have a much lower complexity than the regression. With a series of fitted $\ours(\smax)$ for $\smax$ from some candidate set $\Csc$ (e.g., a uniform grid on $[0,0.5]$), we choose the one with the smallest mean prediction error on the labeled data, i.e., $\ours(\widehat{\smax})$ with
\begin{equation}
    \widehat{\smax} = \underset{\smax\in\Csc}{\arg\min}\   \frac{1}{n_\dagger} \sum_{i=1}^{n_\dagger} \big\{Y^\dagger_i-\ours(\smax)\trans A^\dagger_i\big\}^2.
    \label{eq:tuning}
\end{equation}
Here $1-\widehat{\smax}$ obtained by (\ref{eq:tuning}) can be viewed as an estimate of the optimal weight assigned to the source-mixing model coefficient $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$, with the purpose of optimizing the prediction performance on the target domain among all DORM estimators with $\smax\in\Csc$. As will be justified in Theorem \ref{thm:truerate}, when the joint-mixing regime (\ref{eq:ideal joint}) approximately holds (with small deviation), this tuning procedure is ensured to result in no worse prediction performance compared to $\bar{\beta}_{\mix}$ derived as the optimal choice under (\ref{eq:ideal joint}). In Appendix~\ref{subsec:simu:diffsmax}, we further discuss the tuning of $\smax$ using surrogates when the gold-standard outcome $Y^\dagger$ is completely unavailable on target, and present corresponding simulation results. The experiments demonstrate that our tuning procedure, whether based on the observed outcomes or surrogates, is effective, and DORM is relatively insensitive to the choice of $\smax$.




% When there is strictly no true outcome $Y\uz_i$ observed on the target, one could also use some surrogate outcome $S_i\uz$ as a noisy approximation of $Y^{(0)}_i$ for tuning. In EHR application, $S_i\uz$ could be taken as counts of the main diagnostic codes for the disease outcome $Y\uz_i$; and in clinical studies, $S_i\uz$ could be some early endpoint of the long-term outcome $Y^{(0)}_i$ of our primary interest. In both examples, the surrogate outcome is much easier to collect than the true outcome. As shown in previous work like \cite{li2023maxway}, the linear model for $S_i\uz\sim A_i\uz$ tends to have the same direction as that of $Y_i\uz\sim A_i\uz$ under conditional independence condition $S_i\uz\perp A_i\uz\mid Y\uz_i$ or $Y_i\uz\perp A_i\uz\mid S\uz_i$ that is likely to hold in practice. In this case, a predictive $\beta$ actually corresponds to a large $\widehat{\text{Cor}}(S\uz,\beta\trans A\uz)$ where $\widehat{\text{Cor}}$ denotes the empirical correlation on the target sample. Thus, we propose to choose
% \[
% \widehat{\smax} = \underset{\smax\in\Csc}{\arg\min}~\widehat{\text{Cor}}(S\uz,\ours(\smax)\trans A\uz).
% \]


% {\color{red} Shall we use $Y^\dagger_i$ and $S^\dagger_i$ here as well?}

% When the outcome $Y$ is strictly unavailable for the target, one could instead use a surrogate outcome \(S_i^\dagger\) as a noisy approximation to guide model selection or tuning. For instance, in an EHR-based application, \(S_i^\dagger\) might be the counts of relevant diagnostic codes that approximate the disease outcome; in a clinical study, \(S_i^\dagger\) might represent an early endpoint or biomarker that serves as a proxy for the long-term outcome of primary interest. In both cases, the surrogate outcome is typically easier and less expensive to collect than the actual outcome. 

\section{Methodological extensions}
\label{sec:complicated}

%DORM begins with a fully coupled joint–mixing regime and then models partially coupled target by equipping the conditional model with distributionally robust optimization to protect against deviation from the ideal joint-mixing. In this section we show two statistically principled extensions that make DORM more effective in real-world settings. 

\subsection{Intrinsic sources}
\label{sec:intrinsic}

The mixture regime introduced in Section \ref{subsec:joint-mixing} imposes that the target law $\PP^{(0)}$ is well-approximated by a mixture of the sources $\{\PP^{(l)}\}_{l=1}^L$. As a natural and plausible extension, we now consider a setting where each observed source $l$ itself is a mixture of a smaller collection of latent, \textit{intrinsic} sources $\{\QQ_j\}_{j=1}^m$, and the target can also be approximated by a mixture of these intrinsic sources. In EHR applications, for example, different health systems are observed sources $\{\PP^{(l)}\}_{l=1}^L$, while their patient populations differ in the mixing proportions of some disease subtypes. Some hospitals may see a higher proportion of severe cases than others. In this view, different disease subtypes correspond to the intrinsic sources $\{\QQ_j\}_{j=1}^m$, and the patient distribution at a new target hospital can also be represented as an appropriate mixture of these intrinsic components.

% patient distributions across some source health systems differ in inclusion rules and documentation practices, but patient trajectories often reflect a limited number of clinical phenotypes (e.g. disease subtypes, social-economic status, post‐operative courses). We can thus assume that each hospital’s joint law over $\{X=(A,W),Y\}$ is a mixture over $m \leqslant L$ intrinsic sources $\{\QQ_j\}_{j=1}^m$ that are unobserved and distinguished from each others; hospitals vary in their {mixing proportions} of these components rather than in the components themselves. In this scenario, implementing DORM with these latent sources $\{\QQ_j\}_{j=1}^m$ to approximate the target can lead to better alignments.

In specific, we assume that each observed source distribution $\PP\ul$ is itself a mixture of $m \leqslant L$ intrinsic sources $\{\QQ_j\}$ on $\RR^p$: 
$$
\PP^{(l)} \;=\; \sum_{j=1}^m \pi^*_{lj}\, \QQ_j,\quad \pi^*_{lj}\geqslant 0 , \ \sum_{j=1}^m\pi_{lj}=1 , \forall l \in [L],
$$
and $\Pi^*:=(\pi^*_{lj})_{l,j}$ has full column rank. Each unobserved $\QQ_j$ is assumed to be sufficiently distinct from any mixture of the others. Under these conditions, it is straightforward to show that each $\QQ_j$ admits a linear representation in terms of the observed sources: 
$$
\QQ_j=\sum_{l=1}^L \alpha^*_{jl}\,\PP^{(l)}, \quad \alpha^*_{jl}\in\mathbb{R},\ \sum_{l=1}^L \alpha^*_{jl}=1,\ \forall j \in [m],
$$
where the weight $\alpha^*_{jl}$ could be negative. These intrinsic $\QQ_j$ can be recovered using an approach similar to \citet{katz2019decontamination}, and the key idea is to iteratively remove the part of one observed source that can be explained by another until only irreducible core components remain. In Appendix \ref{sec:appen:latent}, we discuss the formal setup of this problem and the algorithm to recover intrinsic sources. 

% In specific, let $A^*:=(\alpha^*_{jl})\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times L}$ and $\mathcal{A}:=\{A=(\alpha_{jl})\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times L}:~\sum_{l=1}^L \alpha_{jl}=1\}$. One can recover the density function on $\QQ_j$ from the following min-max problem: 
% \begin{equation}
%     \min_A \max_{j\neq k}\ \operatorname{JSD}\left(\suml \alpha_{jl} \PP\ul \mid \suml \alpha_{kl} \PP\ul\right)
% \end{equation}
% where $\operatorname{JSD}(P\mid Q) = \half D_{\KL}(P|M) + \half D_{KL}(Q|M), M=\half(P+Q)$ is Jensen–Shannon divergence between two distributions. 
% \begin{equation*}
%    A^*= \min_{A\in\mathcal{A}} \max_{j\neq k}\ D_{\operatorname{KL}}\left(\suml \alpha_{jl} \mathrm{d}\PP\ul \mid \suml \alpha_{kl} \mathrm{d}\PP\ul\right).
% \end{equation*} 
% This can be further reduced to the density ratios as
% \begin{equation*}
%     \min_A \max_{j\neq k}\ \suml \alpha^*_{jl}\E_{\PP\ul} \log \left[\frac{\suml \alpha^*_{jl} \bar{r}_l(X)}{\suml \alpha^*_{kl} \bar{r}_l(X)}\right]
% \end{equation*}
% where $\bar{r}_l(x)$ is density ratio between observed source $\PP\ul$ and some reference distribution as defined in \eqref{eq:barrl}. As we can estimate density ratio between two source distributions $\PP\ul$ using flexible non-parametric models, this min-max problem is also viable in finite samples. %It is notable that this intrinsic source problem in the context of mixture distribution is also studied in \citet{katz2019decontamination}. In Appendix~\ref{sec:appen:latent} we discuss an alternative formulation of this problem and provide identification and estimation results. 
% [Write it into density ratio, we never estimate density, thus it's flexible and accommodate any ML model. non-paramatric, not depend on any assumption]

After recovering the intrinsic sources $\{\QQ_j\}$, we simply treat $\{\QQ_j\}$ as the ``sources’’ in all DORM constructions. For example, with target covariates distribution $\PP\uz_{X}$, we can project it onto $\mathrm{conv}\{\QQ_j\}$ to obtain target weights $\bar\rho$ and weights $\eta_j(X;\bar\rho)$. As $\QQ_j$'s are linear combinations of $\PP\ul$'s, this is equivalent to extending $\bar\rho \in \Delta_L$ to allow signed affine prior weights $\bar\rho$ with $\sum_l\bar\rho_l = 1$, which can more precisely capture the mixture structure and benefit DORM.


\subsection{Adjusting for pre-mixing covariates}
\label{subsec:adjust}

% In the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint}, the entire joint $(X,Y)$ on the target is modeled as a mixture of source joints. In EHR practice, however, site-specific inclusion rules and coding systems often perturb a subset of variables $X_{\mathcal{D}}\subset X$ (how demographics/comorbidities are recorded, referral patterns, encounter type, etc.), so cross-site differences in $X_{\mathcal{D}}$ are partly administrative. We call these $X_{\Dsc}$ \textit{pre-mixing covariates}, as they can be viewed as measured before the mixing mechanism and do not contribute to mixture weights. By contrast, the remaining covariates $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}=X\setminus X_{\mathcal{D}}$ and the outcome $Y$ are generated by more stable clinical pathways. For example, $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}$ can be surrogates with shared physiology of $Y$, so the conditional law $(X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}$ is much closer across sites than the full joint $(X_{\mathcal{D}},X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)$. 

In the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint}, the target joint law of $(X,Y)$ is fully viewed as a mixture of source joint distributions. In multi-institution EHR data, heterogeneous coding practices often induce systematic shifts in a subset of covariates $X_{\mathcal{D}}\subset X$. %(e.g., how demographics or comorbidities are recorded, referral patterns, encounter types, and other workflow-driven variables)
As a result, cross-site distributional heterogeneity of $X_{\mathcal{D}}$ is partly administrative rather than clinical. We refer to these variables as \textit{pre-mixing covariates}, since they are realized before the mixing mechanism and therefore do not contribute to the mixture weights. By contrast, the remaining covariates $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}=X\setminus X_{\mathcal{D}}$ and the outcome $Y$ are more plausibly governed by shared clinical processes. 
%For instance, $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}$ may include physiological surrogates that relate to $Y$ through common mechanisms, making the conditional law $(X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}$ substantially more stable across sites than the full joint distribution of $(X_{\mathcal{D}},X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)$. 
This suggests that the mixture structure for $\PP_{Y\mid X}$ is better captured in the conditional distribution $\PP_{X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}}$ than the full covariate distribution $\PP_X$.


Motivated by this, we introduce the following data generating mechanism that only $(X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)$ is tied to the source-joint-mixing structure on target:
\begin{equation}
(X_{\mathcal{D}}^{(0)},X_{\mathcal{D}^c}^{(0)},Y^{(0)}) \sim 
\PP^{(0)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}}}\;
\sum_{l=1}^L \rho_l^* \; \PP^{(l)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}}\; \PP^{(l)}_{Y | X_{\mathcal{D}},X_{\mathcal{D}^c}},
\label{eq:cond-joint}
\end{equation}
with $\rho^*\in\Delta_L$. This is an extension of the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled regime \eqref{eq:ideal joint} in the sense that on target population, the marginal distribution $\PP^{(0)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}}}$ is not mixed, while conditional law of $(X_{\mathcal{D}^c},Y)\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}$ follows a mixture of source-specific components $(\PP^{(l)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}},\PP^{(l)}_{Y | X_{\mathcal{D}},X_{\mathcal{D}^c}})$. Accordingly, equation \eqref{eq:cond-joint} defines a covariate-\emph{adjusted} fully coupled regime that generalizes the original formulation. In particular, when $X_{\mathcal{D}}=\emptyset$, it reduces to the regime in \eqref{eq:ideal joint}.

Similarly, we can consider the partially coupled regime that adjusts for the pre-mixing covariates $X_{\Dsc}$ and construct the adjusted DORM estimator. Computationally, this only requires density ratios that we already estimated for the original DORM, because any adjusted density ratio can be written as a ratio of joint and marginal ratios:
\begin{equation}
    \frac{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(0)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}}(X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}})}{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}}(X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}})}
    \;=\;
    \frac{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(0)}(X)}{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}(X)}\ \Big/\ 
    \frac{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(0)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}}}(X_{\mathcal{D}})}{\mathrm{d} \PP^{(l)}_{X_{\mathcal{D}}}(X_{\mathcal{D}})}
    \;=\;
    \frac{w_l(X)}{v_l(X_{\mathcal{D}})},
    \label{eq:cond_dr}
\end{equation}
where $w_l(X)$ is the density ratio for the full covariate vector $X$ between target and source $l$, and $v_l(X_{\mathcal{D}})$ is the density ratio for $X_{\mathcal{D}}$ between target and source $l$. Then, the adjusted weights can be obtained by replacing each use of the marginal density ratio for $X$ in the original DORM construction with the adjusted ratio for $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}$. The identification and estimation of the adjusted DORM procedure are thus analogous to the original DORM, and we provide details in Appendix~\ref{sec:appen:adjust detail}. Our simulation also shows that the adjusted DORM outperforms existing benchmarks, with detailed results reported in Appendix~\ref{appen:condA}. 

As the adjusted conditionals $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}\mid X_{\mathcal{D}}$ and $Y\mid (X_{\mathcal{D}},X_{\mathcal{D}^c})$ are more plausibly governed by shared mixture weights, the induced uncertainty set is smaller and better aligned with the true data-generating distribution, which reduces the conservativeness of DORM and improves predictive performance.



