\section{Simulation study}


\subsection{Data generation and benchmarks}\label{simu:benchmarks}

We conduct extensive simulation studies to evaluate our proposed DORM under various settings and compare it with existing methods. In Section \ref{subsec:simu:Landmix}, we focus on low-dimensional $A$ settings and will compare DORM with benchmarks under various circumstances. In Section \ref{subsec:simu:highd}, we will highlight the improved performance of DORM through comparison with several recently developed multi-source domain adaptation methods with high-dimensional $A$. More details and comprehensive results can be found in Appendix~\ref{appen:sec:add}.

We set $L=5,N_l=2000,n_l=500,N_0=2000$ by default if not specified purposely. The dimension of $X$ is $p = 200$, and for low dimensional settings we set $q = \dim A = 5$. The source data are generated differently for each source site, with both covariate shift and conditional model drift.
% Besides generating $A,W,Y$, we also generate the post-hoc surrogate $S_i\uz$ as 
% \begin{equation}
%     S_i\uz=\nu Y_i\uz + (A_i\uz,W_i\uz)\trans \zeta +\varepsilon_S,
% \label{eq:surrogate}
% \end{equation}
% where $\epsilon_S\sim N(0,0.5^2)$ is noise, $\nu$ would be some moderate number like $0.5$ and $\zeta$ is a sparse vector. 
For each subject $i$ on the target domain ($i \in [N_0]$), we generate $X\uz_i (i \in [N_0]) \sim \PP\uz_X = \suml \rho^*_l \PP\ul_X$ according to a given prior probability $\rho^* \in \Delta_L$, which will be detailed in the following experiments. For $Y\mid X$ on the target domain, we set the unobserved $Y\uz_i$ to follow the partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime in (\ref{eq:Y|Xdist}):
\[ Y\uz_i | X\uz_i \sim \PP\uz_{Y|X} = (1-s^*)\sum_{l=1}^L \eta_l(X;\rho^*) \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)}+ s^* \sum_{l=1}^L \delta_l^* \mathbb{P}_{Y \mid X}^{(l)}, \]
where $s^*$ is the decoupling level and $\delta^* \in \Delta^L$ is an arbitrary probability vector.
%Here the parameter $s^*$ characterizes the violation of the generated data from the ideal joint source-mixing assumption (\ref{eq:ideal joint}). The closer \(s^*\) is to 1, the farther the actual target distribution deviates from this source-mixing assumption. 
% We evaluated how $s^*$ and $\smax$ in our algorithm will influence the performance in detail in subsection \ref{subsec:tunesmax}. 
% {\color{red} In our description of the simulation, it will be better to say: we generate $Y$ from the target domain with various $\delta$. Do not use $Y^{(0)}$. Otherwise, it still sounds like a specific target.}
We evaluate an estimator $\beta$ through its worst-case prediction performance on the uncertainty set of target domain using standardized MSE as the measure. To evaluate distribution robustness and generalizability, we uniformly sample 100 different $\delta^{*(b)}$ on the simplex $\Delta_L$ and report worst-case performance (highest standardized MSE) among the 100 trials ($b=1,2,\cdots,100$). By default, we generate a small $n_\dagger = 20$ labeled sample with $Y^\dagger_i$ to obtain $\widehat{\smax}$ using tuning method in Section \ref{sec:tuning}. We repeat 500 times of simulation for each setting to summarize the numerical performance. The detailed setup for simulation can be found in Appendix \ref{appen:simulationset}. 
% Compared to the previous reward function (\ref{eq:droY}), $L_2$ loss differs only by a constant term \(Y^2\). Since different methods will add the same constant term, comparing $L_2$ loss and comparing reward functions are essentially equivalent to comparing this $L_2$ loss.  We regress $Y\ul$ on low-dimensional $A\ul$ using OLS on each site, getting estimation $\widehat{\beta}\ul$ on each site. 

Our benchmarks include different aggregation strategies of the estimator $\qlh$ in (\ref{eq:qlhat}) and several recently developed high-dimensional domain adaptation approaches that will be mainly compared in Section \ref{subsec:simu:highd}. We summarize the methods under comparison below: 1. \textbf{SimpleAve}: the simple average of each $\qlh$; 2. \textbf{Joint Mixing}: the estimator under the ideal joint-mixing (fully $(X,Y)$-coupled) regime; 3. \textbf{Maximin}: an adaptation of the covariate shift adjusted maximin regression proposed in \cite{guo2022statistical} to our setup (fully $(X,Y)$-decoupled regime); 4. \textbf{TransLasso}: Transfer Lasso approach proposed by \cite{li2022transfer}; 5. \textbf{TransGLM}: Transfer Lasso for generalized linear models proposed by \cite{tian2023transfer}, with a different multi-source aggregation strategy from TransLasso; 6. \textbf{PTL}: Profile Transfer Learning proposed by \cite{lin2024profiled}.

% \begin{enumerate}
%     \item \textbf{SimpleAve}: the simple average of each $\qlh$, $\widehat{\beta}_{\sf SA} = 1/L \suml \qlh$.
%     \item \textbf{Joint Mixing}: the estimator under the ideal joint mixing regime.
%     \item \textbf{CG DRO}: an adaptation of the covariate shift adjusted maximin regression proposed in \cite{guo2022statistical} to our setup.
%     \item \textbf{TransLasso}: Transfer Lasso approach proposed by \cite{li2022transfer}.
%     \item \textbf{TransGLM}: Transfer Lasso for generalized linear models proposed by \cite{tian2023transfer}, with a different multi-source aggregation strategy from TransLasso.
%     \item \textbf{PTL}: Profile Transfer Learning proposed by \cite{lin2024profiled}.
% \end{enumerate}
% {\color{red} Also include other benchmark methods here like Translasso and point out when to compare with them.}



