\subsection{Performance for low-dimensional setting}
\label{subsec:simu:Landmix}
In this subsection, we consider the low-dimensional $A$ setting ($\dim A = 5$) and vary the prior mixture weights $\rho^*$. In Figure~\ref{fig:diff-mix}, we set $L=5$ source sites and evaluate several choices of $\rho^*$. For each setting, we report the worst-case performance across decoupling levels $s^* \in [0,0.5]$. In the first scenario (Figure~\ref{fig:mix0}), the prior mixture is $\rho^* = (0.5, 0, 0.5, 0, 0)$. We observe that, across most decoupling levels, DORM consistently outperforms all benchmarks. When $s^*$ is small ($s^* \in [0.05, 0.20]$), DORM closely tracks Joint Mixing, as expected: DORM is designed to remain robust to departures from full coupling while coinciding with Joint Mixing when full coupling approximately holds. In this regime, DORM also substantially outperforms SimpleAve and Maximin. Under a moderate violation, e.g., $s^* = 0.35$, DORM markedly improves upon both Maximin and Joint Mixing. Joint Mixing deteriorates when $s^*$ is large because the mixing weights $\rho^*$ implied by $X$ are no longer valid. In the second scenario (Figure~\ref{fig:mix2}), we consider a balanced mixture over the first three sites. The results are essentially the same as in Figure~\ref{fig:mix0}, suggesting that mixing evenly over two sites versus three sites yields similar behavior in this setting.
 

% In the second scenario \ref{fig:mix1}, the prior is more unbalanced, with more weight on the first site and less weight on the third site. We can see that our method still outperforms most benchmarks at a moderate $s^*$. We notice that Maximin is almost as good as our method in this unbalanced scenario, which means a moderate uncertainty set has already arrived at the same optimal coefficient as the maximum uncertainty set. In the third scenario \ref{fig:mix2}, we have a balanced mixture among the first three sites. The phenomenon is almost the same as Figure \ref{fig:mix0}, showing that equal mixture of two sites and three sites are similar. 

% In the fourth scenario \ref{fig:mix3}, we assign equal weights to all five source sites. This is not common in the real-world study, especially when the number of sites $L$ is large. For instance, we do not expect that a mixed blood subject is a mixture of all the potential races (with nonnegligible positive weights); instead we expect that it is a mixture of only a few possible races. In our simulation setting, an equal average of all source sites will lead to a regression coefficient near zero, and more violation of ideal mixture actually will bring the coefficient closer to the origin point. Therefore, both adversarial regression methods will perform better when $s^*$ increases. When $s^* = 0.50$, standardized MSE of DORM is 0.9377, which is about 23\% better than RhoAve and SimpleAve. 
% In Figure \ref{fig:diffL}, we conducted the simulation with $L=10$ different source sites, where the last five sites have moderately different distribution from the first five sites. The performances of the methods are quite similar as the $L=5$ scenario in Figure \ref{fig:mix0}. 
% If we shift all source sites to the same direction, the worst-case loss of our method or Maximin will increase. We conducted this center shift simulation in the Appendix \ref{appen:centershift}. 

