In this low-dimensional setting, we also conduct other comprehensive simulations, which are reported in Appendix~\ref{appen:sec:add}; we briefly summarize the main findings here. In Appendix ~\ref{subsec:additional plot}, we vary the prior weights $\rho^\ast$ and the number of sources $L$, and observe a similar pattern in which DORM consistently outperforms competing methods across a range of configurations. 
Appendix~\ref{subsec:simu:diffsmax} examines the tuning strategies for $\smax$ introduced in Section~\ref{sec:tuning} using target outcomes $Y$ and surrogates, and shows that DORM is relatively insensitive to the choice of $\smax$.
In Appendix~\ref{appen:condA}, we evaluate the pre-mixing covariate–adjusted version of DORM from Section~\ref{subsec:adjust} under the low-dimensional regime, and find that it works well and outperforms benchmark methods.
Moreover, in Appendix~\ref{appen:overlap}, we conduct an additional simulation study to demonstrate that DORM is less sensitive to weak overlap in $\PP_X$ between the source and target compared to the common importance weighting strategies.
%, which is a by-product of our proposed construction. This is because our method utilizes the posterior weight $\eta_l (X;\rho)$ that can effectively alleviate the impact of those source samples whose observed covariates deviate significantly from the target distribution.


\subsection{High-dimensional domain adaptation}
\label{subsec:simu:highd}

In this subsection, we compare DORM with state-of-the-art domain adaptation algorithms: TransLasso \citep{li2022transfer}, TransGLM \citep{tian2023transfer} and Profile Transfer Learning \citep{lin2024profiled}. It is important to note that DORM does not need any labels from the target domain in its training procedure, except for tuning $\smax$, while all the methods mentioned above require a decent amount of target labels. We will compare our method with these benchmarks under different setups of the labeled sample size of the target domain.

We focus on a high-dimensional regression setting and set $A = X$ so the dimension of $A$ is $q = 200$. In this setting, we implement DORM with the lasso regularization as described in Appendix \ref{sec:app:regularize}. The source mixture weight is chosen as $\rho^* = (0.5,0,0.5,0,0)$, and the decoupling level $s^* = 0.1$. In Figure \ref{fig:highdim2}, we present the standardized MSE evaluated on the worst-case standardized MSE over different $\delta^*$ under the data generation described in Section~\ref{simu:benchmarks}, and DORM performs better than the other domain adaptation methods. 
%For example, even with the largest sample size $n_0 = 200$, DORM achieves a standardized MSE of 0.9260 evaluated on the target, while TransLasso's is 122.67\% higher than DORM, TransGLM is 42.58\% higher, and PTL is 15.30\% higher. The worst-case performance metric gives a similar result, indicating the effectiveness and robustness of DORM. 

The MSEs of TransLasso, TransGLM, and PTL all increase as the target labeled sample size $n_0$ decreases, while the performance of DORM barely changes with this label size. This is because we only use the target labels for tuning of $\smax$ and this low-dimensional procedure is much less sensitive to the reduction of $n_0$ compared to TransLasso and others. For SimpleAve, $\qlh$ is not influenced by target labeled samples, so its simple aggregation is also constant over different target samples. In our setup, PTL performs better than TransLasso and TransGLM mainly because the latter two are based on the vanishing difference of the regression coefficients between the target and a certain subset of sources for knowledge transfer, overlooking the source-mixing structure of target distribution. PTL regresses the target response on the transferred feature, leading to the profiled responses and calculating the residuals. However, PTL still shows worse performance than DORM since it is ``misspecified'' in our joint-mixing scenario, under which the target model coefficient vector is not necessarily a linear combination of the source model coefficients.


