In Figure~\ref{fig:highdim_contam}, we also evaluate the predictive performance under the contaminated data generation model as indicated by (\ref{eq:contam1}). The contamination distribution $\PP_{Y|X}^{(\varepsilon)}$ is set different from any linear combination of source conditional distributions $\PP_{Y|X}\ul$, and the detailed setup for the target data generation can be found in Appendix \ref{appen:simulationset}. We retain the prior weight as $\rho^* = (0.5,0,0.5,0,0)$, with the true decoupling level $s^* = 0.1$. Figure~\ref{fig:highdim_contam} presents the worst-case standardized MSE and DORM outperforms other benchmarks. With the largest target labeled sample size of $n_0 = 200$, DORM achieves a worst-case standardized MSE of 1.9433, while TransLasso’s is 40.25\% higher, TransGLM’s is 27.11\% higher, and PTL’s is 44.54\% higher. This worst-case performance demonstrates DORM’s robustness to contamination on the target. In Appendix~\ref{appen:subsec:highdim}, we provide more results for the high-dimensional DORM method, showing that DORM performs consistently well in high-dimensions.

%With the largest target labeled sample size of $n_0 = 200$, DORM achieves a standardized MSE of 0.9643, while TransLasso’s is 93.75\% higher, TransGLM’s is 58.34\% higher, and PTL’s is 63.54\% higher. The worst-case performance shows similar trends, demonstrating DORM’s robustness to contamination of the source mixture on the target. 

%PTL is notably impacted in this setting because significant contamination could heavily bias the ensemble weights of the source model coefficients.


\section{Real data analysis}\label{sec:realdata}

We validate our proposed DORM approach using the high-density lipoprotein (HDL) lab test data from Mass General Brigham (MGB) and UK Biobank (UKB) along with the genetic information. It is believed that the genetic underpinnings of mean lipoprotein diameter differ by race/ethnicity. \cite{frazier2013genetic} found that variation across the intronic region of the LIPC gene was suggestively associated with mean HDL diameters only in Caucasians. In our analysis, among the 195 SNPs reported to be associated with mean HDL diameter in \cite{frazier2013genetic}, we focus on those with a minor allele frequency larger than 0.1 in the UKB and MGB cohorts, resulting in 27 SNPs. We then build a linear model on fasting mean HDL diameters for each race-gender subgroup, adjusted for age. In each cohort, aside from the six main racial groups serving as sources, there are a small number of mixed-race groups, with detailed races and their sample sizes in Appendix~\ref{appen:realdata}. Considering these mixtures of sources as the target populations, it is reasonable to assume that the target model is equal/close to the mixture of source models built on the main racial groups. For each target, we randomly sample 50 data points to form the training target label (used to tune DORM and train other benchmarks) and treat the rest as the validation dataset to evaluate the prediction performance on the target site. 

To further assess distributional robustness and generalizability, we construct the validation dataset by selecting the same race–gender subgroup as the training target, but drawn from a different data source. 
%For example, the training target includes UKB unknown females while the validation population comes from MGB unknown females. 
Because MGB only includes two mixed-race target populations (Other and Unknown), the generalizability analysis focuses on portability across genders and these two target races between the two healthcare systems. Ideally, a distributionally robust method should maintain strong performance even when future data arise from a population mildly shifted from the training target. We compare DORM with benchmarks introduced in Section~\ref{simu:benchmarks}, using the coefficient of determination $R^2$ on held-out testing samples as the evaluation metric.

\begin{figure}[htb!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{Pictures/realdata_self.pdf}
    \caption{$R^2$ of different methods when both the training target data and the validation data come from the same cohort. Source sites include 6 major race-gender groups in UKB (European female/male, African female/male, Asian female/male). $R^2$ less than $-200\%$ has been truncated to $-200\%$.}
    \label{fig: real data 1}
\end{figure}

In Figure \ref{fig: real data 1}, we present $R^2$ of DORM and other methods when both the training target and the validation data come from the same population, averaged over genders. DORM outperforms other benchmarks with the highest $R^2$ (MGB mean $R^2$: 1.95\%; UKB mean $R^2$: 3.12\%), while SimpleAve and Joint Mixing suffer from a large negative $R^2$ especially when the training target is UKB Other female/male. Maximin over-shrinks the coefficient to zero, which leads to a small $R^2$ close to zero (MGB mean $R^2$: 0.154\%; UKB mean $R^2$: 0.514\%). The three domain adaptation methods, TransLasso (MGB mean $R^2$: $-4.86\%$; UKB mean $R^2$: $-40.6\%$), TransGLM (MGB mean: $-3.94\%$; UKB mean: $1.50\%$), and PTL (MGB mean: $-7.17\%$; UKB mean: $-3.66\%$) fail to train an efficient model due to the limited number of target labels and site heterogeneity, ending up with poor transferability.

\begin{figure}[htb!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.65\textwidth]{Pictures/realdata_trans.pdf}
    \caption{$R^2$ of different methods when the training target data come from a certain race-gender in one site, and the validation data contain data from the same race-gender subgroup in the same site (diagonal panels) or in a different site (off-diagonal panels). $R^2$ is taken average over genders and those with less than $-200\%$ has been truncated to $-200\%$.}
    \label{fig: real data 2}
\end{figure}


Figure~\ref{fig: real data 2} further evaluates cross-cohort generalization. The off-diagonal panels show $R^2$ when training and validation samples come from the same race--gender subgroup but from different healthcare systems. DORM remains the top under this shift (MGB to UKB: 2.98\%; UKB to MGB: 1.88\%). Maximin (MGB to UKB: 0.08\%; UKB to MGB: 0.24\%) attains the second-highest average $R^2$, suggesting some degree of domain adaptation; however, its performance remains close to zero, consistent with an overly conservative uncertainty set. Except for TransGLM (MGB to UKB: -2.38\%; UKB to MGB: 0.95\%), the remaining benchmarks yield negative $R^2$ in both directions, indicating limited generalizability.





\section{Discussion}

We proposed DORM, a multi-source domain adaptation framework for source-mixture subpopulations, such as admixed ancestry groups in large biobanks. DORM models the partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime and exploits the source-mixing structure to transfer information when target labels $Y$ are scarce or unavailable. The uncertainty set for the partially $(X,Y)$-coupled regime consists of a coupled part identified from interpolation between the fully $(X,Y)$-coupled (joint-mixing) regime and a fully decoupled, unidentifiable component; then DORM optimizes the worst-case performance under this partially identified regime. Our doubly robust implementation further yields nuisance-error-robust and statistically efficient estimation under covariate shift and mixture structure. In both simulations and application, DORM improves predictive performance and out-of-distribution generalizability compared with state-of-the-art multi-source domain adaptation methods.

Several directions remain for future work. First, extending DORM beyond linear models to generalized linear models and flexible machine learning predictors for $Y\sim A$ would broaden applicability but raises new challenges for both solving the resulting saddle problems and interpreting the robust solutions. Second, for interval estimation and hypothesis testing on population-level coefficients, one could adapt resampling-based procedures such as those in \citet{guo2022statistical} to our quadratic-program characterization to handle the non-regularity of maximin-type estimators. 


\section*{Data Availability Statement}

The R code used to conduct our method and simulations is available at \url{https://osf.io/mu6hs/overview?view_only=eef6298c31444a8f840b5d51df9fd34a}. The data that support the real data analysis is available from Mass General Brigham and UK Biobank. Restrictions apply to the availability of these data, which were used under license for this study. 


%Third, our construction of $\eta_l(x)$ relies on an approximate covariate-mixing representation \eqref{eq:xmix}; under severe misspecification, the regime may poorly approximate $\PP^{(0)}_X$ and this cannot be fully diagnosed with unlabeled data in the current setup. Developing more robust and testable procedures for learning and validating the mixing structure remains an important topic for future research.


% We develop DORM, a novel framework for multi-source domain adaptation targeting source-mixture sub-populations such as mixed ethnicity subgroups in our biobank application. DORM takes advantage of the source-mixing structure for effective knowledge transfer under the scarcity or even absence of observations of $Y$ in the target sample. It also incorporates group adversarial learning in order to achieve distributional robustness to the violation of such source-mixing assumptions and improve out-of-distribution generalizability. Meanwhile, our DML approach serves as a novel tool for nuisance-error-robust and efficient estimation in the presence of covariate shift and mixture structure. Importantly, in both the simulation and real-world studies, DORM shows improvement over state-of-the-art multi-source domain adaptation methods in terms of predictive performance and generalizability.

% Finally, we discuss several potential future directions of our work. First, it would be useful to accommodate in DORM generalized linear models (GLMs) and general machine learning models for $Y\sim A$. This could be naturally realized by replacing the linear and least squares reward function $R_{\PP}(\beta)$ with those of GLMs and non-parametric prediction models. Nevertheless, new challenges may arise in both optimization and statistical interpretation. Second, for the interval estimation and testing of our population-level model coefficients, one could potentially leverage the resampling inference approach of \cite{guo2022statistical} to address the non-regularity issue of the maximin estimation. Third, our construction strategy of $\eta_l(x)$ may produce inaccurate approximations of $\PP_X\uz$ on target under severe misspecification of the covariate mixing structure (\ref{eq:xmix}). This issue could also not be examined or identified with the data in our current framework. Fixing this problem may require more advanced techniques for robust learning of mixture distributions, which warrants future research.


