We also evaluate the predictive performance under the contaminated data generation model as indicated by (\ref{eq:contam1}). The contamination distribution $\PP_{Y|X}^{(\varepsilon)}$ is set different from any linear combination of source conditional distributions $\PP_{Y|X}\ul$, and the detailed setup for the target data generation can be found in Appendix \ref{appen:simulationset}. We retain the prior weight as $\rho^* = (0.5,0,0.5,0,0)$, with the true violation level $s^* = 0.1$. Figure \ref{fig:contam} presents the standardized MSE evaluated on the target data and the worst-case standardized MSE. On both evaluation metrics, DORM outperforms other benchmarks. With the largest target labeled sample size of $n_0 = 200$, DORM achieves a standardized MSE of 0.9643, while TransLasso’s is 93.75\% higher, TransGLM’s is 58.34\% higher, and PTL’s is 63.54\% higher. The worst-case performance shows similar trends, demonstrating DORM’s robustness to contamination of the source mixture on the target. 

\subsection{Simulation of adjustment for pre-mixing covariates}
\label{appen:condA}
In this subsection, we present simulation results for DORM with adjustment for pre-mixing covariates, as described in Section~\ref{subsec:adjust}. We consider the same low-dimensional setting for source data generation as in Section~\ref{appen:simulationset}. In our simulation, the pre-mixing covariates in the adjusted model are precisely the low-dimensional block $A$, i.e., we set $X_{\mathcal{D}}=A\in\mathbb{R}^q$ with $q=5$, and let the remaining covariates be $X_{\mathcal{D}^c}=W\in\mathbb{R}^p$. For the target distribution, we generate $A$ using the standard Gaussian distribution $A\uz \sim (1,N_4(0,I_4))$, so the distributional shift in $X_{\mathcal{D}}=A$ is uninformative for the mixing structure. The conditional model for $W\uz|A\uz$ on the target is the same as the generation in \ref{appen:simulationset}. We compare our method \texttt{DORM\underline{ }adj} with the same benchmarks in Section~\ref{simu:benchmarks}, and results are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:adjust DORM}. Across the same range of decoupling levels considered above, the adjusted DORM estimator remains uniformly competitive and typically improves the benchmark methods.



\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{Pictures/CondA_plot_1103 (1).png}
    \caption{The worst-case performance with adjusted DORM, with $L=5$ and prior $\rho^* = (0.5,0,0.5,0,0)$.}
    \label{fig:adjust DORM}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Poor overlapping scenario}
\label{appen:overlap}

It is worth mentioning that our method performs well when the distributions of $X$ on the source and target sites poorly overlap. The poor overlapping distributions of $X$ across the sites can cause the density ratio model $w_l(x)$ to be unbounded and highly varied and, thus, leading to poor efficiency in covariate shift correction through sample reweighting \citep{torrey2010transfer}. Interestingly, our approach could mitigate this issue by learning a posterior probability $\eta_l(X;\bar\rho)$ that assigns smaller weights to more "distant" or less relevant source sites and effectively reduces the risk of negative transfer. 

%In our theoretical framework, we include an overlap parameter $C_w$ in the convergence rates of the DORM estimator. While minimal overlap can increase the convergence rate constant, it actually improves finite-sample predictive performance, as outlined above.

To reveal the effectiveness of the \textbf{posterior weighting} against ordinary density ratio weighting or DML method for covariate shift correction \citep{liu2023augmented}, we carry out an additional simulation study. In this study, we simply set the conditional model $\PP\ul_{Y|X}$ to be identical across all the source and target sites. For $\PP\ul_X$, we make the 1st and 3rd site identical $\PP^{(1)}_X = \PP^{(3)}_X$ with their mean of $X$ close to the origin, while the rest of source sites are following the same distribution $\PP^{(2)}_X = \PP^{(4)}_X = \PP^{(5)}_X$ with their mean far away from the origin. We set the source-mixing weight of the target as $\rho = (0.5,0,0.5,0,0)$ so that the target has a poor overlap with the sources 2, 4 and 5 in $X$'s distribution. We introduce parameter \texttt{COEF-A} to depict the discrepancy in $X$'s distribution between sources 2, 4, 5 and the target, with larger \texttt{COEF-A} representing stronger covariate shift and poorer overlap. Our study include three DML covariate shift corrected estimators for comparison: (1) DORM; (2) Simple Average; and (3) Single, with (1) and (2) introduced in Section \ref{simu:benchmarks} and (3) being $\qlh$ for a randomly picked $\ell\in\{1,\ldots,5\}$ in every experiment. In DORM, we simply set $\smax=0$ considering that all the sources and target share the same model for $Y\mid X$.
 
In Figure \ref{fig:additional} we compared three different methods in terms of their MSE on the target population. We can observe that DORM performs much better than take a simple average or a random choice of single estimator. Also, the poorer overlap between the target and the sources 2, 4, 5, the larger gain our method shows over Simple Average and Single. This is because the posterior weight $\eta_l(X;\bar\rho)$ used in our approach can down-weight the impact of the source data points that deviate too far from the target distribution. 


\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.60\textwidth]{Pictures/Appendix_Overlap.pdf}
    \caption{Mean square error (MSE) under various degrees of covariate distribution overlapping between the sources (2, 4, 5) and target, with larger \texttt{COEF-A} representing stronger covariate shift and poorer overlap.}
    \label{fig:additional}
\end{figure}



